result.execSummary:
The defendant Russell W. Blakney was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Strangulation and Suffocation [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.235(1).
  • Strangulation and Suffocation [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.235(1).
  • Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • False Imprisonment [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.30.
  • Intimidate Victim/Conspiracy [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.45(4).
  • Battery - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Domestic Abuse Repeater (During 72 Hour No Contact Period)], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Use of a Dangerous Weapon, Domestic Abuse Repeater (During 72 Hour No Contact Period)], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The Defendant is to undergo any counseling the agent finds appropriate and must comply with any recommended treatment/assessment/counseling.    The Defendant is to complete the Domestic Violence Intervention Program.  The Defendant is ordered to undergo an anger management assessment and follow any recommendations for counseling. The Defendant is ordered to complete chemical abuse counseling.  The Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety - no alcohol or drugs unless prescribed by a physician. Defendant is to have no contact with victim (no face to face contact unless approved by agent in advance; phone, written, e-mail, texts are allowed).  Defendant is subject to random drug/blood/breath/hair/tissue/UA testing.  The Defendant is not to go into any bars, taverns or businesses where the primary purpose is to sell alcohol. Defendant is to cooperate with psychiatric exam and treatment.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due, and/or other collection means, such as income assignment will be issued.
